            {
              "id": "GHSA-xpw8-rcwv-8f8p",
              "name": "LanguageSpecificPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "io.netty:netty-codec-http2 vulnerable to HTTP/2 Rapid Reset Attack"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "A client might overload the server by issue frequent RST frames. This can cause a massive amount of load on the remote system and so cause a DDOS attack. \n\n### Impact\nThis is a DDOS attack, any http2 server is affected and so you should update as soon as possible.\n\n### Patches\nThis is patched in version 4.1.100.Final.\n\n### Workarounds\nA user can limit the amount of RST frames that are accepted per connection over a timeframe manually using either an own `Http2FrameListener` implementation or an `ChannelInboundHandler` implementation (depending which http2 API is used).\n\n### References\n- https://www.cve.org/CVERecord?id=CVE-2023-44487\n- https://blog.cloudflare.com/technical-breakdown-http2-rapid-reset-ddos-attack/\n- https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/identity-security/google-cloud-mitigated-largest-ddos-attack-peaking-above-398-million-rps/"
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://github.com/advisories/GHSA-xpw8-rcwv-8f8p",
              "help": {
                "text": "Vulnerability GHSA-xpw8-rcwv-8f8p\nSeverity: HIGH\nPackage: io.netty:netty-codec-http2\nFixed Version: 4.1.100.Final\nLink: [GHSA-xpw8-rcwv-8f8p](https://github.com/advisories/GHSA-xpw8-rcwv-8f8p)\nA client might overload the server by issue frequent RST frames. This can cause a massive amount of load on the remote system and so cause a DDOS attack. \n\n### Impact\nThis is a DDOS attack, any http2 server is affected and so you should update as soon as possible.\n\n### Patches\nThis is patched in version 4.1.100.Final.\n\n### Workarounds\nA user can limit the amount of RST frames that are accepted per connection over a timeframe manually using either an own `Http2FrameListener` implementation or an `ChannelInboundHandler` implementation (depending which http2 API is used).\n\n### References\n- https://www.cve.org/CVERecord?id=CVE-2023-44487\n- https://blog.cloudflare.com/technical-breakdown-http2-rapid-reset-ddos-attack/\n- https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/identity-security/google-cloud-mitigated-largest-ddos-attack-peaking-above-398-million-rps/",
                "markdown": "**Vulnerability GHSA-xpw8-rcwv-8f8p**\n| Severity | Package | Fixed Version | Link |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|HIGH|io.netty:netty-codec-http2|4.1.100.Final|[GHSA-xpw8-rcwv-8f8p](https://github.com/advisories/GHSA-xpw8-rcwv-8f8p)|\n\nA client might overload the server by issue frequent RST frames. This can cause a massive amount of load on the remote system and so cause a DDOS attack. \n\n### Impact\nThis is a DDOS attack, any http2 server is affected and so you should update as soon as possible.\n\n### Patches\nThis is patched in version 4.1.100.Final.\n\n### Workarounds\nA user can limit the amount of RST frames that are accepted per connection over a timeframe manually using either an own `Http2FrameListener` implementation or an `ChannelInboundHandler` implementation (depending which http2 API is used).\n\n### References\n- https://www.cve.org/CVERecord?id=CVE-2023-44487\n- https://blog.cloudflare.com/technical-breakdown-http2-rapid-reset-ddos-attack/\n- https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/identity-security/google-cloud-mitigated-largest-ddos-attack-peaking-above-398-million-rps/"
              },
